Project name：City Photo Classification Game
This prototype is designed as an interactive ‘drag-and-drop’ sorting game where users need to match city photos with the correct city labels. The interaction is designed to be simple and intuitive, allowing users to participate through visual recognition and direct manipulation. The core interaction method is "drag and drop," chosen because it is more immersive and proactive than clicking buttons or selecting answers from menus. By dragging and dropping images into designated areas, users can participate more deeply in the sorting process, thus enhancing engagement.
The chosen application scenario for this prototype is **city recognition and cultural geography**, specifically focusing on identifying the visual features of major Chinese cities such as Beijing, Shanghai, and Chongqing. This application scenario has significantly influenced the visual style and usability design. Since city recognition heavily relies on visual memory and landmark recognition, the interface prioritizes image visibility and simplicity. The design avoids unnecessary visual distractions to ensure players can focus on identifying architectural styles, landmarks, and urban environments. (Therefore, all photos were taken by myself.)
The interface uses a "3×3 image grid layout," chosen to ensure clarity and balance. Grid systems are widely considered effective organizational structures because they help users process information efficiently and reduce cognitive load. Based on Jacob Nielsen's usability principles, interfaces should minimize user confusion and support recognition rather than memorization (Nielsen, 1994). Equal spacing and consistent size between images ensure visual hierarchy and predictability, enabling easy user interaction.
The color scheme also reflects the intended usability goals. A soft beige background (#F5F2EB) creates a calming visual environment and reduces eye strain, while blue city labels are chosen because blue is typically associated with trust, clarity, and stability in interface design. Interaction feedback states use strong contrasting colors: yellow for success and red for errors. These colors were chosen because they immediately convey results and are culturally familiar right and wrong indicator colors.
Feedback mechanisms are a crucial part of the design process. The game provides "multimodal feedback," including visual animations, sound effects, and text messages. Correct answers trigger a yellow flashing animation and positive sound feedback, while incorrect answers trigger a red flashing and shaking animation. This design philosophy stems from the game design principle that immediate feedback reinforces user actions, thereby increasing engagement and learning (Norman, 2013). The shaking effect of incorrect answers adds a touch of fun, conveying the feeling of failure without excessively punishing the player.
For users, the simple operating system is easier to use. The effect of hovering over placement areas visually indicates the image's location, helping users understand the interactive functionality. This embodies Don Norman's concept of "perceptual affordance," where users should be able to intuitively understand how to interact with the interface through visual cues (Norman, 2013). Furthermore, draggable cards become semi-transparent during movement, helping users understand the interaction state and maintaining visual continuity.
One of the anticipated advantages of expanding this prototype into a larger project is scalability. By expanding the `gameData` array, more cities, landmarks, and even educational categories can be easily added. Dozens of photos can also be randomly placed within a 3x3 image grid, with a random combination on each refresh. This flexibility means the system has the potential to develop into a broader platform for geographical, travel, or cultural learning and education. Features such as difficulty levels and timers can also enhance user engagement and playability.
In summary, this prototype demonstrates how combining interaction design, usability principles, and multimodal feedback can create an experience that is both fun and educational. It also made me realize how visual simplicity and optimized responsive systems can be engaging and enhance the user experience.

